<document>
	<title>Cystic fibrosis: a HLA associated hereditary disease?.</title>

	<author>Kaiser-G-I.</author>
	<author>Laszlo-A.</author>
	<author>Gyurkovits-K.</author>

	<source>Acta-Paediatr-Acad-Sci-Hung. 1977. 18(1). P 27-9.</source>

	<abstract>Twelve homozygote patients and thirty-two heterozygote gene carriers
   from families with cystic fibrosis were HLA-typed. Diagnostic
   criteria were sweat electrolyte concentration, pancreatic enzyme
   levels from duodenal juice and stool, Szczepanski&apos;s bromide test in
   the group of homozygotes, and the latter only in the cases of
   heterozygotes. In comparison with 130 healthy blood donors typed for
   29 HLA antigens. B18 proved to be more frequent in the group of
   patients and gene carriers, with 50 and 31%, respectively, and 14% in
   the normal population. The association seems to be stronger in the
   homozygotes than in the heterozygotes (p less than 0.02,
   respectively).</abstract>

